            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Simone Shapiro\u2019s identity was forged at the intersection of Oakland\u2019s vibrant Black culture and Berkeley's intellectual Jewish tradition. The only child of a Black social worker and a white history professor, Simone\u2019s childhood was filled with lively debates on social justice at the dinner table and a deep-seated belief that systems could, and should, be made to work for everyone. She grew up riding the AC Transit bus across the Bay, keenly aware of how access to transportation defined the boundaries of opportunity.\n\nThis awareness guided her to UC Davis, where she pursued a degree in Public Policy, focusing on urban planning. After graduation, she spent five years working for a non-profit advocating for equitable housing before realizing she wanted to be on the inside, turning policy into practice. She took a position with the SFMTA, seeing it as the city\u2019s complex, often-maligned, but essential circulatory system. Over a decade, she worked her way up to Program Manager, known for her pragmatic approach and unwavering focus on user experience.\n\nA key turning point came during a massive public outreach campaign for a new bus route. Facing a room of angry residents, she didn't just present data; she shared her own stories of waiting for late buses in the rain. This authentic connection became her professional trademark. Her 14.8-mile commute from her small Outer Sunset condo to her office downtown is both a daily grind and a point of professional pride. Riding the N-Judah, she isn't just a manager; she's a customer, taking mental notes on everything from timeliness to cleanliness.\n\nHer life is structured but not rigid. Weekdays are for work, but evenings are for yoga and her tight-knit book club. Weekends are for long walks along Ocean Beach, letting the fog clear her head, and exploring the city\u2019s culinary scene with a few close friends. At 37, she feels a quiet contentment with her career but a lingering desire for a deeper partnership. Her dream isn\u2019t lofty; it\u2019s tangible. She wants to see a major accessibility project through to completion\u2014one that will genuinely improve the daily lives of thousands of commuters, herself included. For Simone, improving the city isn't just a job; it's the defining purpose of her life."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was ten, her hand held tight in her mother\u2019s at the AC Transit stop on International Boulevard. It was raining, and the bus was late, again. Simone watched the exhaustion settle onto her mom\u2019s face, a daily tax levied by a broken system. It wasn't just an inconvenience; it felt like a theft of time and energy. In that moment of shared frustration, the abstract dinner-table debates about justice became a cold, concrete reality. A quiet, fierce resolve took root: she would be someone who made the buses run on time.\n\n2.\nAt 28, she sat in her housing non-profit office, the small victory of a delayed eviction feeling hollow. Looking out at a Muni bus pulling away, she felt a profound shift. She had spent years advocating from the outside, writing reports and lobbying officials. But she realized then she didn\u2019t just want to influence the people with the blueprints; she wanted to be one of them. She wanted her hands on the levers, turning policy from a hopeful theory into the sturdy, reliable infrastructure of people's daily lives.\n\n3.\nThe community hall was a sea of angry faces. Her PowerPoint slides about the new bus route felt useless. Taking a breath, she put the clicker down. \"I get it,\" she began, voice steadier than she felt. \"I spent my childhood waiting for buses in the rain.\" The room quieted. A flicker of recognition passed between her and an elderly woman in the front row. In that shared moment, she wasn\u2019t a bureaucrat; she was a rider. It taught her that empathy wasn't a soft skill, but the most powerful data she had.\n\n4.\nLast Tuesday, stalled on the N-Judah near Duboce Park, she watched a man using a walker easily board thanks to a new platform her team had spent 18 months on. No one else noticed, but Simone\u2019s heart swelled with a quiet, fierce pride. This wasn\u2019t a headline-grabbing project, but for that one person, on that one morning, the city worked. This commute wasn\u2019t just a grind; it was her daily, tangible proof of purpose. She took out her phone and made a note about the door\u2019s closing speed.\n\n5.\nA recent Saturday evening, walking where the pavement of the Great Highway met the sand. The fog over Ocean Beach was so thick it muffled the world, softening the city\u2019s sharp edges. Her life was good, structured, meaningful. But in the quiet space between the foghorn's low call and the surf\u2019s reply, a different longing surfaced\u2014not for a different life, but for someone to share this one with. Someone to walk beside her as the city, and her own heart, settled for the night."
